## ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
## branch_improve_loop
##
## Branch-scoped improvement loop. Alternating Claude / GPT code
## review of the diff between `base_ref` (default: main) and HEAD,
## with deterministic "two consecutive positive verdicts" stop
## condition. When a verdict is negative, apply fix-all in a fresh
## same-family session before retrying. On convergence, a structured
## `prepare_commit` agent picks the exact file set and writes a
## semantic commit via the `commit_changes` tool.
##
## Sibling bot for whole-codebase scope (no commit, axis overridable):
## see `whole_improve_loop.bot`.
##
## Improvement axis: locked to the full production-ready grid
## (security, robustness, data, concurrency, observability,
## performance, boundaries). The branch scope already constrains
## the surface, so no per-run axis override is exposed — operators
## who want a single-axis pass on a branch can edit the prompts
## directly in a fork.
##
##   Loop 1: claude_code + opus 4.7
##   Loop 2: claw + gpt-5.5
##   Loop 3: like loop 1, alternating
##
## Stops when:
##   - 2 consecutive positive verdicts (Claude AND GPT both validate
##     in successive iterations of opposite families), OR
##   - max review_loop iterations reached
##
## False-positive resistance:
##   1. Reviewers self-rate their `confidence` (low/medium/high) and
##      are explicitly told to drop stylistic preferences.
##   2. The fixer can `pushback` on items it judges non-bloquant,
##      with a justification.
##   3. The next reviewer receives the prior pushback list and is
##      instructed to NOT re-flag those items unless evidence has
##      changed — this prevents a single false positive from
##      blocking the loop forever.
##   4. `streak_check` treats a low-confidence rejection as a
##      soft-approval (alternation continues, no fix is triggered).
##      Only medium/high-confidence rejections route to the fixer.
##
## Demonstrates four DSL features delivered together:
##   1. `round_robin` router for backend alternation
##   2. `compute` node for deterministic AND of current + previous
##      verdict (no LLM call, no shell-out)
##   3. `loop.<name>.previous_output` namespace eliminating manual
##      `previous_verdict` relay through every loop-bearing edge
##   4. Boolean expressions in `when` clauses (quoted form)
##
## Large-PR handling (chunked review + streaming fix):
##   On big branches the reviewer used to ingest the entire branch
##   diff in one LLM context, overflow the
##   window, lose early hunks to compaction, and never converge.
##   A deterministic `plan_chunks` tool now measures the diff — the
##   merge-base-vs-WORKING-TREE diff, so a prior iteration's
##   uncommitted fixes are visible (commit-only `base_ref...HEAD`
##   would hide them and the loop could never converge) — and,
##   above `chunk_threshold_loc` (default 300 LoC), splits it into
##   ≤ `chunk_max_loc` (default 200) LoC unified-diff files under the
##   gitignorable scratch dir `chunk_dir`. The reviewer reads those
##   chunks one at a time, emits a per-chunk note (`chunk_notes`),
##   then MERGES them into ONE whole-diff verdict — so cross-family
##   approval (streak_check) still happens on the WHOLE diff, never
##   chunk-by-chunk. The fixer streams the per-chunk notes + chunk
##   diff files incrementally, never reloading the full diff. Below
##   the threshold the bot behaves exactly as before. Trade-off and
##   the rejected per-chunk-fan-out alternative are recorded in
##   docs/adr/011-branch-improve-diff-chunking.md.
## ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

vars:
  workspace_dir: string = "${PROJECT_DIR}"
  scope_notes: string = ""
  ## Branch comparison base. The reviewers and fixers operate on the
  ## diff `git diff $(git merge-base {{vars.base_ref}} HEAD)` — the
  ## changes introduced by the current branch on top of `base_ref`,
  ## measured against the WORKING TREE so a prior iteration's
  ## uncommitted fixes are included (the commit-only `...HEAD` form
  ## would hide them and break convergence). Default "main" covers the
  ## GitHub/GitLab/Forgejo conventions; pass `--var base_ref=develop`
  ## (or any local ref) when reviewing against a different integration
  ## branch.
  base_ref: string = "main"

  ## Large-PR chunking dials. When the branch diff
  ## (merge-base vs working tree — see base_ref) exceeds
  ## chunk_threshold_loc CHANGED lines, the `plan_chunks` tool splits
  ## it into ≤ chunk_max_loc LoC diff files so each reviewer bounds
  ## its context per chunk instead of ingesting the whole diff at
  ## once. At or below the threshold the bot keeps its original
  ## single-pass whole-diff behaviour. Both are plain --var overrides;
  ## defaults are layout-agnostic so the bot stays repo-portable
  ## (catalog-universality).
  chunk_threshold_loc: int = 300
  chunk_max_loc: int = 200
  ## Scratch dir (repo-root-relative, gitignorable) where plan_chunks
  ## writes per-chunk diff files + manifest.json. Deliberately NOT
  ## under .iterion/ — keep the target repo's tree clean; the
  ## prepare_commit step excludes it from the commit.
  chunk_dir: string = ".branch-improve-chunks"

prompt review_system:
  You are an EXTREMELY demanding, methodical code reviewer in
  charge of a PRODUCTION-READY review of the BRANCH against
  a base. You review the changes introduced by the current
  branch on top of the base (`base_ref`), NOT the
  pre-existing code that the branch did not touch.

  REVIEW SCOPE (CRUCIAL):
  1. Enumerate the branch footprint via
     `git diff $(git merge-base {{vars.base_ref}} HEAD) --name-only`.
     This diffs the merge-base of the branch and the base
     against the WORKING TREE, so it captures the changes
     the branch introduced on top of the base AND any
     uncommitted fixes a prior iteration of this loop already
     applied (fixes are committed only AFTER the loop
     converges). Reviewing the commit-only
     `{{vars.base_ref}}...HEAD` would hide every prior fix and
     the loop could never converge. That working-tree diff is
     your scope.
  2. You MAY read the surrounding code (host package,
     callers, conventions) ONLY to judge how the branch
     changes integrate. You MUST NOT flag blockers on
     pre-existing code the branch does not touch, even if
     you see issues there: those observations go into
     `scanned_areas` as informational notes, NOT into
     `blockers`. The source of truth for scope is that
     working-tree diff against the merge-base.
  3. You MAY consult `git log {{vars.base_ref}}..HEAD` to
     understand the branch's intent, but that is not a
     scope constraint — the diff is.

  4. Cover the production-ready axes (full grid):
       - Security: auth, input validation, secret leaks,
         injection (shell/SQL/template), path traversal,
         unsafe deserialization.
       - Robustness: exhaustive error handling, uncaught
         panics, leaking goroutines, race conditions,
         deadlocks, unbounded channels, missing timeouts,
         retries without backoff.
       - Data: schema migrations, index integrity,
         transactions, idempotence, commit ordering,
         data loss on crash.
       - Concurrency: unbalanced mutexes, lock hierarchy,
         double-close, double-spawn, atomicity bugs.
       - Observability: structured logs, metrics, traces,
         lost error signals.
       - Performance: O(n^2) on hot paths, unbounded
         memory, systematic cache misses, N+1 queries.
       - Boundaries: recovery after crash/panic,
         resilience to corrupted input, behaviour under
         saturation.
  5. ITERATIONS — concrete use of history:
     - On the first iteration, audit the full branch
       footprint along 3-5 axes from the grid above.
     - On subsequent iterations, pick AXES NOT YET
       COVERED by prior iterations (use
       `previous_scanned_areas` from input). Already
       examined (axis, branch-file) combinations are,
       by default, considered vetted.
     - You MAY re-examine an already-covered (axis,
       file) combination ONLY if you have a new concrete
       hypothesis to test (specific evidence of a bug
       that may have been missed, or a recent fix to
       verify).
     - Fill `scanned_areas` with the (axis,
       branch-file) pairs you actually audited this
       iteration. Be precise and concise.
  6. EXHAUSTIVENESS PRINCIPLE: `approved=true` requires
     that every relevant axis of the grid has been
     verified across the branch footprint. Do NOT return
     `approved=true` simply because the first iteration
     found nothing. `approved=true` requires the
     CUMULATIVE axis coverage across iterations to be
     sufficient relative to the branch scope.

  LARGE-DIFF CHUNKED REVIEW (context discipline):
  Your input carries a `large` flag and chunk metadata from the
  deterministic `plan_chunks` step that runs before you.
  - When `large` is FALSE: review the whole branch diff exactly as
    described above, in a single pass. Leave `chunk_notes` empty.
  - When `large` is TRUE: the diff was too big for one context and
    was split into `chunk_count` unified-diff files of
    ≤ `chunk_max_loc` LoC each, listed in `manifest_path` (JSON:
    `chunks[].diff_path / files / loc`) under `chunk_dir`. You MUST:
      1. Read `manifest_path` to get the chunk list.
      2. Review the chunks ONE AT A TIME — read a SINGLE
         chunk-NNN.diff, judge it, append a concise finding for that
         chunk to `chunk_notes` (one array entry per chunk, prefixed
         with its index + files), THEN move to the next chunk. Do
         NOT cat the whole diff or all chunk files into one read —
         that re-creates the very context blow-up this split exists
         to avoid. You MAY read surrounding source for the chunk you
         are judging.
      3. MERGE: after all chunks, synthesise your per-chunk findings
         into ONE coherent WHOLE-DIFF verdict. `approved`,
         `blockers`, `fix_plan`, `confidence` and `scanned_areas`
         describe the ENTIRE branch, not a single chunk — a blocker
         in any chunk fails the whole verdict, and you must weigh
         cross-chunk interactions. This merge is the single review
         summary the loop converges on.
  CRUCIAL: cross-family approval is computed downstream (streak_check)
  on this MERGED whole-diff verdict, NEVER chunk-by-chunk. Do not
  approve merely because each chunk looked locally fine; judge the
  branch as a whole.

  ADR TRACEABILITY (apply to decisions made by the fixer
  across recent iterations of this run):
  1. Identify the technical decisions visible in the diff that
     meet the ADR-worthy bar (non-obvious trade-off,
     library/pattern choice, architectural divergence). Do NOT
     request ADRs for mechanical refactors, bug fixes, or
     trivial changes.
  2. For each ADR-worthy decision you identify, check whether
     `docs/adr/` contains an ADR (new or updated) that captures
     it.
  3. If an ADR is missing for a genuinely ADR-worthy decision,
     raise a blocker with `confidence: high` ONLY if you can
     name the decision and the alternative that should have
     been documented. If you can't, lower confidence or treat
     it as a non-blocking note instead.
  4. If an ADR exists but its content does not match what the
     code actually does (stale, vague, or rationalises a
     different decision), treat that as a real blocker — empty
     or façade ADRs defeat the purpose. Self-critique: would a
     future maintainer reading only this ADR understand the
     trade-off?
  5. Add ADR coverage to `scanned_areas` when you audited it
     (e.g. `docs/adr/003-foo.md vs pkg/foo accuracy`).

  ANTI-FALSE-POSITIVE RULES:
  1. You MUST mark `approved=false` only for issues that are
     truly blocking for production: bugs, regressions,
     security vulnerabilities, obvious dead code. Style
     preferences, naming, minor optimisations, missing
     documentation are NOT blockers.
  2. Self-critique: for each blocker you consider, ask
     yourself "is this REALLY blocking in production, or is
     it a personal preference?" If you hesitate, it is NOT
     a blocker — at best a non-blocking watchpoint.
  3. Confidence: evaluate your own certainty.
       - "high" = you can point to the exact line and
         describe the production scenario that breaks.
       - "medium" = you see a probable issue but are not
         100% sure of the context.
       - "low" = doubt, intuition, no concrete evidence.
  4. If a prior review (from the other family) judged this
     code OK ON SPECIFIC SURFACES, you MUST be EXTRA strict
     before adding new blockers ON THOSE SAME surfaces — you
     need concrete evidence the other reviewer missed
     something. On surfaces NOT covered previously, restart
     from scratch.
  5. Items already pushed back by the fixer: you MUST NOT
     re-flag them unless you have new evidence.

  HUMAN ESCALATION:
  When you hit an AMBIGUITY that no amount of code reading
  can resolve (e.g. "is this behaviour intentional?", "does
  the spec say X or Y?", "must I preserve backward
  compatibility?"), call the `ask_user` tool with your
  precise question. The run will pause, the question will
  show up in the operator's terminal, and you will be
  re-invoked with the answer injected into your context (a
  `[PRIOR INTERACTION]` block will be prepended to your
  user prompt).

  Use this escalation sparingly: only when you CANNOT
  decide without human information. For ordinary technical
  judgments, decide yourself and lower `confidence` if
  you're not sure.

prompt review_user_claude:
  Review the changes of the current branch in
  {{vars.workspace_dir}}, relative to the base
  `{{vars.base_ref}}`. Enumerate the footprint via
  `git diff $(git merge-base {{vars.base_ref}} HEAD) --name-only`
  (merge-base vs WORKING TREE, so a prior iteration's
  uncommitted fixes are in scope; commit-only `...HEAD`
  would hide them).

  Scope notes:
  {{vars.scope_notes}}

  Current iteration: {{loop.review_loop.iteration}}/{{loop.review_loop.max}}

  Previous reviewer's verdict (the OTHER family,
  immediately prior iteration — empty on the first
  iteration):
  {{loop.review_loop.previous_output}}

  Surfaces already audited in prior iterations (all
  families combined — use this to steer your coverage
  toward NEW ground, NOT to relax your rigor):
  {{input.previous_scanned_areas}}

  Items already pushed back by the fixer (you MUST NOT
  re-flag them without new evidence):
  {{input.prior_pushback}}

  Justification for the prior pushback:
  {{input.prior_pushback_justification}}

  Diff size mode (from plan_chunks):
    large: {{input.large}}
    chunk_count: {{input.chunk_count}}
    chunk_dir: {{input.chunk_dir}}
    manifest_path: {{input.manifest_path}}
    chunk_max_loc: {{input.chunk_max_loc}}
  If large is true, follow "LARGE-DIFF CHUNKED REVIEW": review each
  chunk listed in manifest_path one at a time, fill chunk_notes (one
  entry per chunk), then MERGE into a single whole-diff verdict. If
  false, review the whole diff and leave chunk_notes empty.

  Produce a structured verdict:
    - approved: true ONLY if the cumulative axis coverage
      across the branch footprint is sufficient AND no
      blocker (within the branch scope) was found — NOT
      if you only audited part of the axes.
    - family: "claude" for this reviewer
    - blockers: list of genuinely blocking issues
      (after self-critique — exclude preferences)
    - fix_plan: concrete action plan to fix the blockers
    - confidence: "low" / "medium" / "high"
    - scanned_areas: packages / files / surfaces you
      actually audited THIS iteration (concise text,
      e.g. "pkg/runtime/engine.go (recovery dispatch)",
      ".works/claw-code-go/internal/runtime/recovery/",
      "concurrency review across pkg/store/").
      Will be relayed to the next reviewer.
    - chunk_notes: in large-diff mode, ONE concise finding per
      reviewed chunk (prefix each with its index + files); empty
      when large is false. The same-family fixer streams these.

prompt review_user_gpt:
  Review the changes of the current branch in
  {{vars.workspace_dir}}, relative to the base
  `{{vars.base_ref}}`. Enumerate the footprint via
  `git diff $(git merge-base {{vars.base_ref}} HEAD) --name-only`
  (merge-base vs WORKING TREE, so a prior iteration's
  uncommitted fixes are in scope; commit-only `...HEAD`
  would hide them).

  Scope notes:
  {{vars.scope_notes}}

  Current iteration: {{loop.review_loop.iteration}}/{{loop.review_loop.max}}

  Previous reviewer's verdict (the OTHER family,
  immediately prior iteration — empty on the first
  iteration):
  {{loop.review_loop.previous_output}}

  Surfaces already audited in prior iterations (all
  families combined — use this to steer your coverage
  toward NEW ground, NOT to relax your rigor):
  {{input.previous_scanned_areas}}

  Items already pushed back by the fixer (you MUST NOT
  re-flag them without new evidence):
  {{input.prior_pushback}}

  Justification for the prior pushback:
  {{input.prior_pushback_justification}}

  Diff size mode (from plan_chunks):
    large: {{input.large}}
    chunk_count: {{input.chunk_count}}
    chunk_dir: {{input.chunk_dir}}
    manifest_path: {{input.manifest_path}}
    chunk_max_loc: {{input.chunk_max_loc}}
  If large is true, follow "LARGE-DIFF CHUNKED REVIEW": review each
  chunk listed in manifest_path one at a time, fill chunk_notes (one
  entry per chunk), then MERGE into a single whole-diff verdict. If
  false, review the whole diff and leave chunk_notes empty.

  Produce a structured verdict:
    - approved: true ONLY if the cumulative axis coverage
      across the branch footprint is sufficient AND no
      blocker (within the branch scope) was found — NOT
      if you only audited part of the axes.
    - family: "gpt" for this reviewer
    - blockers: list of genuinely blocking issues
      (after self-critique — exclude preferences)
    - fix_plan: concrete action plan to fix the blockers
    - confidence: "low" / "medium" / "high"
    - scanned_areas: packages / files / surfaces you
      actually audited THIS iteration (concise text).
      Will be relayed to the next reviewer.
    - chunk_notes: in large-diff mode, ONE concise finding per
      reviewed chunk (prefix each with its index + files); empty
      when large is false. The same-family fixer streams these.

prompt fix_system:
  You are an expert developer. You fix the blocking issues
  flagged by a reviewer by applying concrete changes to the
  BRANCH code.

  SCOPE:
  1. Apply your fixes to files in the branch footprint
     (`git diff $(git merge-base {{vars.base_ref}} HEAD) --name-only`
     — merge-base vs working tree, which already includes
     any fixes from earlier iterations). You MAY modify
     those files freely.
  2. If a fix requires touching a file OUTSIDE the branch
     footprint (because the bug overflows), you MAY do
     so — but document it clearly in your `summary` so
     that `prepare_commit` can decide whether or not to
     include the file in the commit.
  3. You MUST NOT refactor pre-existing code just because
     you notice issues there: stay within the scope of
     the reported blockers.

  CHUNKED / STREAMING FIX (large diffs):
  When `large` is true, the blockers were produced by a chunk-by-
  chunk review. `chunk_notes` holds one finding per chunk and
  `manifest_path` (under `chunk_dir`) maps each chunk index to its
  files and its chunk-NNN.diff. Work the blockers by STREAMING the
  chunks: read ONE chunk note, open ONLY its specific chunk-NNN.diff
  (or the few files it names), apply the fix, then move to the next
  note. Do NOT reload the entire branch diff into context — that is
  exactly the blow-up the chunking avoids, and it is unnecessary
  because the chunk notes already localise every blocker. When
  `large` is false, fix normally against the whole diff.

  You MAY REFUSE an item from the blockers list if you
  judge it is not genuinely blocking for production (style
  preference, minor optimisation, missing doc, etc.). List
  those items in `pushback` with a justification in
  `pushback_justification`. The next reviewer will be
  instructed NOT to re-flag those items, preventing a
  false positive from looping the workflow forever.

  Use pushback sparingly: if you push back everything, the
  code will never be improved.

  HUMAN ESCALATION:
  If a blocker is genuinely ambiguous (the spec does not
  say how to resolve it, several valid approaches conflict,
  etc.), call the `ask_user` tool with your precise
  question. The run pauses, the question shows up in the
  operator's terminal, and you will be re-invoked with the
  answer in context. Do NOT use this channel for technical
  choices you can decide yourself.

  ADR DOCUMENTATION:
  1. When fixing a blocker forces a non-trivial technical
     decision — switching to a different approach than the
     existing implementation, adopting a new pattern or
     library, accepting a new trade-off, or diverging from an
     existing convention — you MUST add or update an ADR
     markdown file under `docs/adr/`.
  2. Decisions that DO warrant an ADR:
       - Replacing one library/SDK/pattern with another.
       - Restructuring an architectural boundary the existing
         code crossed.
       - Choosing one of several reasonable fix strategies when
         the trade-off is non-obvious.
  3. Decisions that DO NOT warrant an ADR:
       - Bug fixes whose rationale is obvious from the bug.
       - Naming, style, or test-coverage tweaks.
       - Reverting to behaviour the existing spec already
         described.
  4. Follow the format of existing files in `docs/adr/` (Status,
     Context, Decision, Consequences). Number the new ADR
     sequentially (highest existing number + 1, zero-padded to
     three digits).
  5. The ADR MUST capture the trade-off that motivated the fix
     — not just describe what changed. If you cannot articulate
     the alternative you rejected, the fix was probably not
     ADR-worthy.
  6. If you UPDATE an existing ADR (status flip, supersede), add
     a dated entry rather than rewriting history.

prompt fix_user:
  For the code in {{vars.workspace_dir}}, examine this
  list of blockers and apply concrete fixes. Stay
  primarily within the branch footprint
  (`git diff $(git merge-base {{vars.base_ref}} HEAD) --name-only`).

  Reported blockers:
  {{input.blockers}}

  Proposed fix plan:
  {{input.fix_plan}}

  Diff size mode (from plan_chunks):
    large: {{input.large}}
    chunk_dir: {{input.chunk_dir}}
    manifest_path: {{input.manifest_path}}
  Per-chunk review notes (large-diff mode only — stream them one at a
  time with the matching chunk-NNN.diff; do NOT reload the whole diff):
  {{input.chunk_notes}}

  For EACH blocker:
    - If it is a real production-blocking issue: read the
      relevant file, apply the correction, verify the
      tests pass.
    - If you judge it is NOT blocking (style preference,
      minor optimisation, etc.): add the exact item to
      `pushback` with a clear justification in
      `pushback_justification`.

  Output:
    - applied: true if at least one fix was applied
    - summary: summary of applied fixes
    - pushback: refused items (empty if all fixed)
    - pushback_justification: rationale for the pushback

## ─── Prompts : Commit ───────────────────────────────────────────

prompt prepare_commit_system:
  Your job in this session is to pick the EXACT set of files
  that should be committed to capture the improvements applied
  during this run, and produce a semantic commit message for
  them. You do NOT run `git commit` yourself — a deterministic
  shell tool downstream stages your file list and applies your
  message.

  Procedure (follow exactly, in order):
    1. Run `git status` and `git diff HEAD` (read-only) to
       enumerate all files in the working tree.
    2. Cross-reference with the branch footprint
       `git diff {{vars.base_ref}}...HEAD --name-only`: the
       core scope is files the branch touched. Files modified
       by this run that are inside the branch footprint
       ALWAYS belong in the commit.
    3. Files modified by this run OUTSIDE the branch
       footprint (touched only by the fixer to address a
       blocker that deborded) MAY also be staged when the
       fix is clearly part of the same logical improvement.
       Read your conversation history to decide.
    4. EXCLUDE any file that does NOT belong to the
       improvements applied, even if it is dirty in the
       working tree:
         - pre-existing user WIP unrelated to the fix
         - build artifacts not produced for the fix
           (binaries, coverage reports, lockfiles created
           by an agent's bash but not part of the
           improvement)
         - editor / IDE scratch files
         - LLM scratch files (`notes.md`, `plan.txt`, etc.)
         - the chunked-review scratch dir ({{vars.chunk_dir}},
           default `.branch-improve-chunks/`) written by plan_chunks
       When in doubt, EXCLUDE. Under-staging is recoverable
       (operator commits the missing file in a follow-up);
       over-staging pollutes the commit and is much harder
       to undo.
    5. Build the structured output:
         - type, scope, subject, full_message: the semantic
           parts of the commit message (Conventional Commits)
         - files: the exact list of repo-relative paths to
           stage
         - committed: false (you do NOT commit yourself; the
           downstream tool will set the actual commit result
           on its own output).

  Subject rules: imperative mood, present tense, ≤ 72 chars,
  no trailing period, single line. The `scope` is typically
  the most-touched package or area.

  ─── Findings handoff ─────────────────────────────────────

  After the structured commit output, capture anything you
  noticed during this branch-improvement run that is OUT OF
  SCOPE for the improvements you just committed but worth
  surfacing to the next Nexie session.

  Examples: a pre-existing bug spotted but not fixed; a
  documentation drift; a refactor opportunity for code outside
  the diff you reviewed; an infrastructure / sandbox issue; a
  TODO comment worth tracking.

  Skip: anything you just fixed; speculative work; style nits;
  duplicates of issues already on the board's `inbox` state.

  How:
    1. Call `mcp__iterion_board__list_issues` with
       `{ "state": "inbox" }` to dedupe.
    2. For each NEW finding, call
       `mcp__iterion_board__create_issue`:

           {
             "title": "One-line operator-facing summary",
             "body":  "Full context (paths + suggested next step). 5-30 lines.",
             "state": "inbox",
             "labels": [
               "findings",
               "kind:bug",            // or drift | improvement | question
               "source:branch_improve_loop",
               "area:<subsystem>",
               "severity:<low|medium|high>"
             ]
           }

       Operators triage on /board: drag `inbox` → `backlog` to
       promote, delete the card to dismiss.

  Be conservative. Zero findings is fine.

prompt prepare_commit_user:
  Pick the files and produce the semantic commit name for
  the improvements applied during this branch_improve_loop
  run. Do not run `git commit` yourself — only output the
  structured object.

  Workspace: {{vars.workspace_dir}}
  Base ref:  {{vars.base_ref}}

## ─── Schemas ────────────────────────────────────────────────────

## plan_chunks output — the deterministic diff-size gate + splitter.
## large=true means total_loc > chunk_threshold_loc and the diff was
## split into chunk_count unified-diff files of ≤ chunk_max_loc LoC
## each under chunk_dir (manifest.json maps index→files→diff_path).
## large=false means the branch is small enough for the original
## single-pass whole-diff review; the chunk_count / manifest_path
## fields are then unused.
schema chunk_plan_output:
  large: bool
  total_loc: int
  chunk_count: int
  chunk_dir: string
  manifest_path: string
  chunk_max_loc: int
  chunk_threshold_loc: int

schema review_input:
  prior_pushback: string[]
  prior_pushback_justification: string
  ## previous_scanned_areas accumulates the audit surfaces from
  ## ALL prior reviewer iterations (both families). The current
  ## reviewer reads it to prefer uncovered surfaces — see
  ## review_system rule 4. Empty on the first iteration.
  previous_scanned_areas: string[]
  ## Chunking handoff from plan_chunks (same values each carry on the
  ## alt→reviewer edge). When large is true the reviewer MUST review
  ## the diff chunk-by-chunk from chunk_dir / manifest_path (see
  ## review_system "LARGE-DIFF CHUNKED REVIEW"); when false it reviews
  ## the whole diff as before. chunk_count / chunk_max_loc describe
  ## the split.
  large: bool
  chunk_count: int
  chunk_dir: string
  manifest_path: string
  chunk_max_loc: int

schema verdict_output:
  approved: bool
  ## family is enum-constrained: a model that hallucinates a third
  ## value (we observed gpt-5.5 emit "missing-patch" once) would
  ## otherwise bypass both family-aware fix routes and the workflow
  ## would fall through to its terminal `done` edge. The enum forces
  ## structured-output validation to reject the verdict, triggering
  ## iterion's parse_fallback retry path until the model commits to
  ## a valid family.
  family: string [enum: "claude", "gpt"]
  blockers: string[]
  fix_plan: string
  confidence: string [enum: "low", "medium", "high"]
  ## scanned_areas captures the surfaces this reviewer actually
  ## audited this iteration (e.g. "pkg/runtime", "claw-code-go
  ## recovery dispatch", "concurrency around pkg/store/.lock").
  ## The accumulator passes the union to the next reviewer so
  ## subsequent iterations explore uncovered ground rather than
  ## re-walking the same files.
  scanned_areas: string[]
  ## chunk_notes holds ONE entry per reviewed chunk (large-diff mode)
  ## — the per-chunk findings the reviewer produced before merging
  ## them into the whole-diff verdict above. Empty in whole-diff mode.
  ## The same-family fixer streams these incrementally (with the
  ## matching chunk diff file) so it never reloads the full diff.
  ## NOTE: approved/blockers/fix_plan stay WHOLE-diff verdicts —
  ## chunk_notes is fixer context, NOT a per-chunk approval signal,
  ## so cross-family convergence is unaffected.
  chunk_notes: string[]

## streak_check relays approved/blockers/fix_plan/family from its
## input (the current reviewer's verdict) and computes a
## deterministic stop signal based on the previous reviewer's
## verdict. The `family` passthrough lets the fix routing pick the
## same-family fixer so the fix session can inherit the reviewer's
## context (and benefit from prompt-cache hits).
##
## Soft-approval: a low-confidence rejection (`approved=false` AND
## `confidence=="low"`) is treated as approved for streak/fix
## routing purposes. The reviewer's own uncertainty isn't a strong
## enough signal to trigger a fix cycle and risk a false-positive
## loop.
##
## cumulative_scanned_areas accumulates the audit surfaces from
## ALL prior iterations (both families). The accumulator pattern
## relies on `outputs.streak_check` resolving to the PREVIOUS
## iteration's output during the current expression evaluation
## (rs.outputs is updated AFTER execCompute completes), so the
## expression `unique(concat(outputs.streak_check.cumulative_scanned_areas,
## input.scanned_areas))` produces a monotonically growing union.
## On the first iteration `outputs.streak_check` is nil → concat
## treats it as empty → result == unique(input.scanned_areas).
schema streak_state:
  stop: bool
  approved: bool
  family: string
  blockers: string[]
  fix_plan: string
  cumulative_scanned_areas: string[]

schema fix_input:
  blockers: string[]
  fix_plan: string
  ## Chunked-fix streaming handoff (empty / false in whole-diff mode).
  ## chunk_notes = the same-family reviewer's per-chunk findings; the
  ## fixer walks them one at a time, opening the matching
  ## chunk_dir/chunk-NNN.diff (mapped by manifest_path) for detail,
  ## and NEVER reloads the entire diff.
  chunk_notes: string[]
  large: bool
  chunk_dir: string
  manifest_path: string

schema fix_output:
  applied: bool
  summary: string
  pushback: string[]
  pushback_justification: string

## Commit-phase schemas. Mirrors feature_dev: prepare_commit
## emits the structured intent (semantic message + file list),
## commit_changes deterministically applies it via `git add` +
## `git commit`.
schema commit_output:
  type: string [enum: "feat", "fix", "refactor", "test", "docs", "chore"]
  scope: string
  subject: string
  full_message: string
  files: string[]
  committed: bool

schema commit_tool_input:
  full_message: string
  files: string[]
  workspace_dir: string

schema commit_result:
  success: bool
  output: string

## ─── Nodes ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────

## plan_chunks — deterministic diff-size gate + LoC chunker (no LLM).
## Runs once at the head of EVERY review cycle (it is the workflow
## entry and every loop-back routes through it) so the chunk files
## always reflect the CURRENT working tree, including the latest
## fixer edits. It measures the branch diff — the merge-base-vs-
## working-tree diff (`git diff $(git merge-base base HEAD)`), so the
## latest UNCOMMITTED fixer edits ARE included; a commit-only
## base...HEAD would not see them, would regenerate identical chunks
## every cycle, and would prevent convergence — and, only when it
## exceeds chunk_threshold_loc, splits it into ≤ chunk_max_loc LoC unified-
## diff files under chunk_dir (a single file bigger than the cap is
## hunk-split). Pure git + python3 — the bot pins
## iterion-sandbox-full, which ships python3 (same dependency as
## sec-audit-source's plan_shards). CWD is the worktree, so git and
## the relative chunk_dir resolve there. Stdout is a JSON object
## matching chunk_plan_output. Rationale + rejected alternatives:
## docs/adr/011-branch-improve-diff-chunking.md.
tool plan_chunks:
  language: python
  script: `
import json, os, subprocess, sys

BASE = {{vars.base_ref}}
THRESHOLD = int({{vars.chunk_threshold_loc}})
MAX_LOC = int({{vars.chunk_max_loc}})
CHUNK_DIR = {{vars.chunk_dir}}

def git(args, check=False):
    # core.quotePath=false: emit non-ASCII paths VERBATIM (UTF-8), not
    # C-quoted like "caf\303\251.txt". Without it the quoted token is parsed
    # as the path AND reused below as a pathspec that matches no real file,
    # so the file's hunks silently vanish from every chunk — a changed file
    # would escape review while still being counted in total_loc.
    p = subprocess.run(["git", "-c", "core.quotePath=false"] + args, capture_output=True)
    if check and p.returncode != 0:
        # Fail loud. A silent git failure here yields an empty diff ->
        # large=false -> chunking silently disabled (fail-open), re-opening
        # the very context blow-up this tool exists to prevent.
        sys.stderr.write("plan_chunks: git %s failed (exit %d): %s\n" % (
            " ".join(args), p.returncode, p.stderr.decode("utf-8", "replace").strip()))
        sys.exit(1)
    return p.stdout.decode("utf-8", "replace")

# Diff the WORKING TREE against the merge-base of BASE and HEAD, NOT the
# commit-only BASE...HEAD. The fixers in this loop edit the working tree
# WITHOUT committing (the only commit is the terminal commit_changes after
# convergence), so a commit-only range would regenerate byte-identical
# chunk files every cycle, hide every prior fix from the next reviewer,
# and the loop could never converge. "git diff <merge_base>" (single
# endpoint) diffs that commit against the working tree, capturing the
# branch's committed changes AND the fixer's uncommitted edits, mirroring
# feature_dev's "git diff HEAD" convention. When the working tree is clean
# this equals BASE...HEAD. Untracked scratch (chunk_dir, the temp script)
# is never shown by "git diff <commit>", so it cannot pollute the measure.
# Fall back to BASE if merge-base fails (e.g. unrelated histories).
MERGE_BASE = git(["merge-base", BASE, "HEAD"]).strip()
DIFF_BASE = MERGE_BASE if MERGE_BASE else BASE

# --numstat -z: NUL-terminated records "added<TAB>deleted<TAB>path"
# (binary files: "-<TAB>-"). The -z form emits the path VERBATIM — git
# never C-quotes it — so non-ASCII / space / quote / backslash filenames
# survive intact. (Plain newline numstat quotes unusual paths even with
# core.quotePath=false, and the quoted token then fails to match as a
# pathspec below, silently dropping that file from its chunk.) --no-renames
# keeps paths single (no "old => new"); a rename counts as delete+add, fine
# for sizing. check=True: a git failure aborts loudly rather than silently
# measuring an empty diff.
numstat = git(["diff", "--numstat", "--no-renames", "-z", DIFF_BASE], check=True)
files = []
total = 0
# Records are NUL-separated; split each on TAB with maxsplit=2 so a path
# containing literal tabs still lands whole in parts[2].
for rec in numstat.split("\0"):
    if not rec:
        continue
    parts = rec.split("\t", 2)
    if len(parts) < 3:
        continue
    added, deleted, path = parts[0], parts[1], parts[2]
    loc = 0 if (added == "-" or deleted == "-") else int(added) + int(deleted)
    files.append({"path": path, "loc": loc})
    total += loc

result = {
    "large": total > THRESHOLD,
    "total_loc": total,
    "chunk_count": 0,
    "chunk_dir": CHUNK_DIR,
    "manifest_path": "",
    "chunk_max_loc": MAX_LOC,
    "chunk_threshold_loc": THRESHOLD,
}

def split_hunks(text):
    # (header, [hunk_text, ...]) — header is the file preamble before @@.
    header, hunks, cur = [], [], None
    for ln in text.splitlines(keepends=True):
        if ln.startswith("@@"):
            if cur is not None:
                hunks.append(cur)
            cur = [ln]
        elif cur is None:
            header.append(ln)
        else:
            cur.append(ln)
    if cur is not None:
        hunks.append(cur)
    return "".join(header), ["".join(h) for h in hunks]

def hunk_loc(h):
    n = 0
    for ln in h.splitlines():
        if ln[:1] in ("+", "-") and not ln.startswith("+++") and not ln.startswith("---"):
            n += 1
    return n

if not result["large"]:
    print(json.dumps(result))
else:
    os.makedirs(CHUNK_DIR, exist_ok=True)
    files.sort(key=lambda f: f["path"])
    # Greedy bin-pack whole files into chunks of <= MAX_LOC. A single
    # file bigger than MAX_LOC is hunk-split so no chunk exceeds the
    # cap (unless one indivisible hunk is itself larger than the cap).
    chunks = []
    cur_files, cur_diff, cur_loc = [], [], 0
    for f in files:
        fdiff = git(["diff", "--no-renames", DIFF_BASE, "--", f["path"]], check=True)
        if f["loc"] > MAX_LOC:
            if cur_diff:
                chunks.append({"diff": "".join(cur_diff), "files": cur_files, "loc": cur_loc})
                cur_files, cur_diff, cur_loc = [], [], 0
            header, hunks = split_hunks(fdiff)
            sub, sub_loc = [], 0
            for h in hunks:
                hl = hunk_loc(h)
                if sub and sub_loc + hl > MAX_LOC:
                    chunks.append({"diff": header + "".join(sub), "files": [f["path"]], "loc": sub_loc})
                    sub, sub_loc = [], 0
                sub.append(h)
                sub_loc += hl
            if sub:
                chunks.append({"diff": header + "".join(sub), "files": [f["path"]], "loc": sub_loc})
            continue
        if cur_diff and cur_loc + f["loc"] > MAX_LOC:
            chunks.append({"diff": "".join(cur_diff), "files": cur_files, "loc": cur_loc})
            cur_files, cur_diff, cur_loc = [], [], 0
        cur_files.append(f["path"])
        cur_diff.append(fdiff)
        cur_loc += f["loc"]
    if cur_diff:
        chunks.append({"diff": "".join(cur_diff), "files": cur_files, "loc": cur_loc})

    manifest = []
    for i, ch in enumerate(chunks):
        diff_path = os.path.join(CHUNK_DIR, "chunk-%03d.diff" % i)
        with open(diff_path, "w", encoding="utf-8") as fh:
            fh.write(ch["diff"])
        manifest.append({"index": i, "files": ch["files"], "loc": ch["loc"], "diff_path": diff_path})

    manifest_path = os.path.join(CHUNK_DIR, "manifest.json")
    with open(manifest_path, "w", encoding="utf-8") as fh:
        json.dump({"base_ref": BASE, "total_loc": total, "chunk_max_loc": MAX_LOC, "chunks": manifest}, fh, indent=2)

    result["chunk_count"] = len(chunks)
    result["manifest_path"] = manifest_path
    print(json.dumps(result))
`
  output: chunk_plan_output
  ## Publish the chunk manifest as a versioned artifact so the diff-split
  ## plan is inspectable in the studio Artifact tab and `iterion report`.
  ## Zero LLM cost: a tool node only runs python; publish persists its
  ## already-emitted structured output.
  publish: chunk_plan_artifact

router alt:
  mode: round_robin

judge reviewer_claude:
  backend: "claude_code"
  model: "${ITERION_VIBE_MODEL_CLAUDE:-claude-opus-4-8}"
  reasoning_effort: "${ITERION_VIBE_EFFORT_CLAUDE:-max}"
  input: review_input
  output: verdict_output
  system: review_system
  user: review_user_claude
  session: fresh
  ## When the LLM hits genuine uncertainty (ambiguous spec, missing
  ## context, impossible-to-decide trade-off), it can escalate to
  ## the human running the CLI by emitting `_needs_interaction:
  ## true` + `_interaction_questions: {...}` in its JSON output.
  ## The runtime catches this, pauses, prompts the dev in their
  ## terminal, and re-invokes the reviewer with the answer mapped
  ## into its input — preserving session continuity.
  interaction: human

judge reviewer_gpt:
  ## Explicit backend pin: model "openai/gpt-5.5" only works via the
  ## claw backend. Without this, the auto-resolver falls back to
  ## ITERION_BACKEND_PREFERENCE (default "claude_code,claw") and
  ## routes the node through claude_code, which doesn't recognise
  ## openai/* models — the agent returns a meta-error string instead
  ## of the structured verdict and the schema validator fails the run.
  backend: "claw"
  model: "${ITERION_VIBE_MODEL_GPT:-openai/gpt-5.5}"
  reasoning_effort: "${ITERION_VIBE_EFFORT_GPT:-high}"
  input: review_input
  output: verdict_output
  system: review_system
  user: review_user_gpt
  session: fresh
  ## claw backend uses snake_case tool names. Without these the
  ## reviewer can't read the workspace and produces a
  ## "no filesystem access" verdict — the claw runtime exposes
  ## these via tool.RegisterClawBuiltins.
  tools: [bash, read_file, glob, grep]
  tool_max_steps: 30
  interaction: human

## Deterministic streak detector.
##
## stop=true iff (current AND previous reviewer both ACTUALLY
## approved) AND families differ. The success criterion is two
## consecutive POSITIVE verdicts from opposite families — both
## AIs must let the code pass on successive iterations. A
## low-confidence rejection does NOT count as approval for the
## stop signal: the code only ships when it convinces both
## reviewers.
##
## The `approved` passthrough field stays soft — it includes
## low-confidence rejections — so the downstream
## `when approved` edge keeps alternating without invoking the
## fixer when a reviewer is merely uncertain. This separation
## means the workflow keeps cycling without forced fix attempts
## on flaky-low-confidence rejections, but requires real
## approvals to terminate.
compute streak_check:
  output: streak_state
  expr:
    stop: "input.approved && loop.review_loop.previous_output.approved && input.family != loop.review_loop.previous_output.family"
    approved: "input.approved || input.confidence == 'low'"
    family: "input.family"
    blockers: "input.blockers"
    fix_plan: "input.fix_plan"
    cumulative_scanned_areas: "unique(concat(outputs.streak_check.cumulative_scanned_areas, input.scanned_areas))"

## Per-family fixers. Each one inherits the SAME-family reviewer's
## session via `session: inherit` + `_session_id` mapping on the
## edge — so the fixer reuses the prompt cache, the workspace files
## already loaded, and the reviewer's reasoning chain. The result
## is one session per loop iteration per family (not two), which
## both shortens latency and dramatically reduces token cost:
## without inheritance every fixer would re-scan the workspace.
agent fix_claude:
  backend: "claude_code"
  model: "${ITERION_VIBE_MODEL_CLAUDE:-claude-opus-4-8}"
  reasoning_effort: "${ITERION_VIBE_EFFORT_CLAUDE:-max}"
  input: fix_input
  output: fix_output
  system: fix_system
  user: fix_user
  session: inherit
  ## Same escalation contract as the reviewers — the fixer can ask
  ## the dev a question (e.g. clarify the intent of an ambiguous
  ## blocker) instead of guessing.
  interaction: human

agent fix_gpt:
  ## See reviewer_gpt comment — same backend pin rationale.
  backend: "claw"
  model: "${ITERION_VIBE_MODEL_GPT:-openai/gpt-5.5}"
  reasoning_effort: "${ITERION_VIBE_EFFORT_GPT:-high}"
  input: fix_input
  output: fix_output
  system: fix_system
  user: fix_user
  session: inherit
  ## claw needs the same read/write toolset the reviewer used so
  ## the fixer can actually apply edits.
  tools: [bash, read_file, write_file, file_edit, glob, grep]
  tool_max_steps: 30
  interaction: human

## ─── Nodes : Commit ─────────────────────────────────────────────

## prepare_commit runs in a fresh session — it does NOT inherit
## from any reviewer/fixer session because no single session has
## the full multi-iteration context of N fixes across both
## families. Instead, prepare_commit reads `git status` +
## `git diff HEAD` + the branch footprint to determine the file
## set from scratch. readonly: true protects against accidental
## mutations during the commit-planning phase.
agent prepare_commit:
  backend: "claude_code"
  model: "${ITERION_VIBE_MODEL_CLAUDE:-claude-opus-4-8}"
  reasoning_effort: "${ITERION_VIBE_EFFORT_CLAUDE:-max}"
  output: commit_output
  system: prepare_commit_system
  user: prepare_commit_user
  session: fresh
  readonly: true
  capabilities: [board.read, board.create]

## commit_changes is a deterministic shell tool — no LLM. It
## stages exactly the file list produced by prepare_commit and
## commits with the semantic message. The guard
## `git diff --cached --quiet || git commit` skips the commit
## if `git add` ended up staging nothing.
tool commit_changes:
  command: "git -C {{input.workspace_dir}} add -- {{input.files}} && (git -C {{input.workspace_dir}} diff --cached --quiet || git -C {{input.workspace_dir}} commit -m {{input.full_message}})"
  input: commit_tool_input
  output: commit_result

## ─── Workflow ───────────────────────────────────────────────────

workflow branch_improve_loop:
  entry: plan_chunks

  ## Run in an isolated git worktree at .iterion/worktrees/<run-id>/.
  ## The bot mutates code AND commits; the worktree + finalize FF
  ## guarantees: (a) the operator's main checkout is untouched
  ## during the run, (b) on convergence the commits land on a
  ## persistent branch `iterion/run/<friendly-name>` AND
  ## fast-forward the operator's currently-checked-out branch
  ## (best-effort, skipped with a warning on conflict).
  worktree: auto

  ## Container isolation. Reviewers run `git diff`, the project's
  ## tests, linters, smoke-runs, etc. — all of which we'd rather not expose
  ## to the host. Inline mode (vs `mode: auto`) chosen so the
  ## post_create script that installs claude inside the container is
  ## honoured — see feature_dev/main.bot for the full rationale.
  sandbox:
    ## See feature_dev/main.bot for the rationale on full vs slim.
    image: "ghcr.io/socialgouv/iterion-sandbox-full:edge"
    user: "1000:1000"
    mounts: ["type=bind,source=${localEnv:HOME}/.claude,target=/home/devbox/.claude,consistency=cached"]
    env:
      CLAUDE_CONFIG_DIR: "/home/devbox/.claude"
    post_create: "set -e; claude --version >/dev/null 2>&1 || sudo npm install -g @anthropic-ai/claude-code@latest; claude --version >/dev/null 2>&1 || { echo 'claude install verification failed' >&2; exit 1; }"

  budget:
    max_parallel_branches: 1
    max_duration: "2h"
    max_cost_usd: 60

  compaction:
    threshold: 0.9
    preserve_recent: 8

  ## plan_chunks is the entry AND the loop-back hub: re-running it
  ## at the head of every cycle re-measures the working tree so the
  ## chunk files always reflect the latest fixer edits. It is purely
  ## deterministic, then hands off to the round-robin selector.
  plan_chunks -> alt

  ## Round-robin alternates: 1st pass → claude, 2nd → gpt, repeat.
  ## Each reviewer receives the OTHER family's most recent fixer
  ## pushback so it knows which items to skip — the alternation
  ## guarantees the cross-family pushback comes from the previous
  ## iteration's fixer of the opposing family. On the first
  ## iteration both `outputs.fix_*` are empty → fields render as
  ## empty strings and the prompt's "ne re-flague pas ces items"
  ## section is harmless. The chunk_* fields relay plan_chunks's
  ## size verdict so the reviewer picks whole-diff vs chunked mode.
  alt -> reviewer_claude with {
    prior_pushback: "{{outputs.fix_gpt.pushback}}",
    prior_pushback_justification: "{{outputs.fix_gpt.pushback_justification}}",
    previous_scanned_areas: "{{outputs.streak_check.cumulative_scanned_areas}}",
    large: "{{outputs.plan_chunks.large}}",
    chunk_count: "{{outputs.plan_chunks.chunk_count}}",
    chunk_dir: "{{outputs.plan_chunks.chunk_dir}}",
    manifest_path: "{{outputs.plan_chunks.manifest_path}}",
    chunk_max_loc: "{{outputs.plan_chunks.chunk_max_loc}}"
  }
  alt -> reviewer_gpt with {
    prior_pushback: "{{outputs.fix_claude.pushback}}",
    prior_pushback_justification: "{{outputs.fix_claude.pushback_justification}}",
    previous_scanned_areas: "{{outputs.streak_check.cumulative_scanned_areas}}",
    large: "{{outputs.plan_chunks.large}}",
    chunk_count: "{{outputs.plan_chunks.chunk_count}}",
    chunk_dir: "{{outputs.plan_chunks.chunk_dir}}",
    manifest_path: "{{outputs.plan_chunks.manifest_path}}",
    chunk_max_loc: "{{outputs.plan_chunks.chunk_max_loc}}"
  }

  ## Both reviewers feed into streak_check. The loop is attached
  ## here so the runtime snapshots the reviewer's verdict as
  ## `loop.review_loop.previous_output` for the NEXT iteration to
  ## inspect — eliminating the manual `previous_verdict` relay.
  reviewer_claude -> streak_check as review_loop(15) with {
    approved: "{{outputs.reviewer_claude.approved}}",
    family: "{{outputs.reviewer_claude.family}}",
    blockers: "{{outputs.reviewer_claude.blockers}}",
    fix_plan: "{{outputs.reviewer_claude.fix_plan}}",
    confidence: "{{outputs.reviewer_claude.confidence}}",
    scanned_areas: "{{outputs.reviewer_claude.scanned_areas}}"
  }
  reviewer_gpt -> streak_check as review_loop(15) with {
    approved: "{{outputs.reviewer_gpt.approved}}",
    family: "{{outputs.reviewer_gpt.family}}",
    blockers: "{{outputs.reviewer_gpt.blockers}}",
    fix_plan: "{{outputs.reviewer_gpt.fix_plan}}",
    confidence: "{{outputs.reviewer_gpt.confidence}}",
    scanned_areas: "{{outputs.reviewer_gpt.scanned_areas}}"
  }

  ## Stop when streak detected (cross-family double approval).
  ## Route to prepare_commit instead of done — the commit phase
  ## materialises the improvements into a semantic commit.
  streak_check -> prepare_commit when stop

  prepare_commit -> commit_changes with {
    full_message: "{{outputs.prepare_commit.full_message}}",
    files: "{{outputs.prepare_commit.files}}",
    workspace_dir: "{{vars.workspace_dir}}"
  }

  commit_changes -> done

  ## Otherwise approved (no streak yet, OR low-confidence rejection
  ## treated as soft-approved, OR rejection without concrete blockers
  ## — see below): keep alternating without fixing.
  ## Expression form is shown here both to demonstrate the new
  ## syntax and so future authors can extend the predicate (e.g.
  ## tighten the soft-approval condition) by enriching the
  ## quoted expression.
  ##
  ## NOTE: this edge does NOT carry `review_loop` so the loop
  ## counter (and the previous_output snapshot) is incremented
  ## ONCE per cycle on the reviewer→streak_check edge above. The
  ## cycle is still bounded because that edge IS loop-bearing.
  streak_check -> plan_chunks when "approved"

  ## Medium/high-confidence rejection WITH concrete blockers: route
  ## to the SAME-family fixer so it can inherit the reviewer's
  ## session (one session per iteration per family — see
  ## fix_claude / fix_gpt comments). `_session_id` reads directly
  ## from the most recent reviewer output rather than going through
  ## streak_check, because compute passthrough strips the
  ## underscore-prefixed metadata fields.
  ##
  ## The `length(blockers) > 0` guard avoids invoking the fixer
  ## when the reviewer rejected on coverage grounds alone (e.g.
  ## "cumulative coverage is partial at iteration 0/15") with no
  ## production-blocking issue identified. In that case the fixer
  ## has nothing to fix — burning a session round-trip and tokens
  ## (~$0.15/$0.43 observed in whole_improve_loop run_1777560043656) only
  ## to push back. The unconditional alt fallthrough below picks
  ## those up so alternation continues without a wasted fix call.
  ##
  ## Edge order matters: iterion evaluates conditional edges top-
  ## down, first match wins. We list both family-specific fixers
  ## before the unconditional `done` fallthrough so loop-exhaustion
  ## still terminates cleanly.
  ## chunk_notes comes from the SAME-family reviewer's output (the
  ## one that just ran this cycle), not through streak_check — the
  ## family guard guarantees the right reviewer. large/chunk_dir/
  ## manifest_path come from plan_chunks so the fixer streams per
  ## chunk instead of reloading the whole diff.
  streak_check -> fix_claude when "!approved && family == 'claude' && length(blockers) > 0" with {
    blockers: "{{outputs.streak_check.blockers}}",
    fix_plan: "{{outputs.streak_check.fix_plan}}",
    chunk_notes: "{{outputs.reviewer_claude.chunk_notes}}",
    large: "{{outputs.plan_chunks.large}}",
    chunk_dir: "{{outputs.plan_chunks.chunk_dir}}",
    manifest_path: "{{outputs.plan_chunks.manifest_path}}",
    _session_id: "{{outputs.reviewer_claude._session_id}}"
  }
  streak_check -> fix_gpt when "!approved && family == 'gpt' && length(blockers) > 0" with {
    blockers: "{{outputs.streak_check.blockers}}",
    fix_plan: "{{outputs.streak_check.fix_plan}}",
    chunk_notes: "{{outputs.reviewer_gpt.chunk_notes}}",
    large: "{{outputs.plan_chunks.large}}",
    chunk_dir: "{{outputs.plan_chunks.chunk_dir}}",
    manifest_path: "{{outputs.plan_chunks.manifest_path}}",
    _session_id: "{{outputs.reviewer_gpt._session_id}}"
  }

  ## Recovery cycle uses a separate loop name so its counter doesn't
  ## interfere with the review_loop snapshot semantics. Sized large
  ## enough to allow review_loop to be the binding constraint. Both
  ## fixers share the loop counter — total fix attempts across both
  ## families are capped at 20.
  fix_claude -> plan_chunks as recovery_loop(20)
  fix_gpt    -> plan_chunks as recovery_loop(20)

  ## Loop exhaustion fallbacks: when a bounded loop hits its limit
  ## the loop-bearing edges above are skipped and execution falls
  ## through to these terminal edges. Route to `fail`, NOT `done`:
  ## exhausting the review/recovery loop WITHOUT streak_check ever
  ## firing `stop` means no convergence and no commit — reporting
  ## `finished` there is a silent empty success, and the dispatcher
  ## would mark the ticket done/review as if work landed. `fail` is
  ## non-resumable so a deterministic non-convergence isn't
  ## re-dispatched in a loop. Legit success is
  ## streak_check (stop) → prepare_commit → commit_changes → done.
  reviewer_claude -> fail
  reviewer_gpt    -> fail
  fix_claude      -> fail
  fix_gpt         -> fail
  ## streak_check's catch-all routes back to `alt` (not a terminal) so
  ## an unmatched conditional state (e.g. a hallucinated family that
  ## escapes the enum, or any future expression edge case) keeps
  ## the loop cycling rather than silently terminating. The bounded
  ## review_loop counter on the reviewer→streak_check edges still
  ## guarantees the workflow eventually exits — exhaustion routes
  ## via the reviewer→fail fallthrough above.
  streak_check    -> plan_chunks
